				\begin{document}$$ \sigma_{\Delta T} = \frac{{E_{f} }}{{1 - v_{f} }}\left( {a_{s} - a_{f} } \right)\Delta T $$\end{document}where Ef and νf are the Young’s modulus and Poisson’s ratio for the films; αf and αs are the thermal expansion coefficients for the films and the substrate. The typical Ef, νf and thermal expansion coefficient of perovskite are 20.5 GPa, 0.33 and 6.1 × 10–5 K−1, respectively, and the typical thermal expansion coefficient of glass is 3.7 × 10–6 K−1 [19, 24]. If the temperature decreases from 80 to 30 °C, a tensile stress of 87.66 MPa can form in perovskite film.

Perovskite itself can form local stress/strain in its lattice. Goldschmidt tolerance factor (t), (RA + RX)/[2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
